Here's an implementation of a binary search tree (BST) insertion in Java. This code includes a `Node` class to represent individual nodes in the tree and a `BST` class to manage the tree.

### Node Class

```java
// Node.java

public class Node {
    int value;
    Node left;
    Node right;

    public Node(int value) {
        this.value = value;
        this.left = null;
        this.right = null;
    }
}
```

### BST Class

```java
// BST.java

public class BST {
    Node root;

    public BST() {
        this.root = null;
    }

    /**
     * Insert a new value into the binary search tree.
     *
     * @param value The value to be inserted.
     */
    public void insert(int value) {
        root = insertRecursive(root, value);
    }

    /**
     * Recursive helper method to insert a value into the binary search tree.
     *
     * @param node  The current node.
     * @param value The value to be inserted.
     * @return The updated node.
     */
    private Node insertRecursive(Node node, int value) {
        if (node == null) {
            return new Node(value);
        }

        if (value < node.value) {
            node.left = insertRecursive(node.left, value);
        } else if (value > node.value) {
            node.right = insertRecursive(node.right, value);
        } else {
            System.out.println("Value already exists in the tree.");
        }

        return node;
    }

    /**
     * Print the binary search tree in-order.
     */
    public void printInOrder() {
        printInOrderRecursive(root);
    }

    /**
     * Recursive helper method to print the binary search tree in-order.
     *
     * @param node The current node.
     */
    private void printInOrderRecursive(Node node) {
        if (node != null) {
            printInOrderRecursive(node.left);
            System.out.print(node.value + " ");
            printInOrderRecursive(node.right);
        }
    }
}
```

